l philosophers Gilles Deleuze and Paul Virilio.Key FeaturesEngaging polemic which connects Scottish literature with critical theory and continental thinking with Scottish philosophy.Provides a needed corrective to the 'theory-fear' which has often stopped Scotland looking at its own Enlightenment.Offers the first book-length commentary on contemporary Scottish writers, as well as re-positioning more familiar writers such as Muriel Spark and James Kelman."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aCriticismxScotland. 0aCriticismzScotland. 0aScottish literaturexHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aScottish literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etcx20th century. 0aScottish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aScottish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074862711040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748627110423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748627110/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK